</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[128,654,211,1424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
ETYMOLOGY: The genus-group name is a combination of 
<emphasis box="[361,386,1013,1037]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">za</emphasis>
(Greek, ‘‘very’’) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[128,228,1043,1067]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[128,228,1043,1067]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the genus of bethylid wasps that the first fossil scolebythid, i.e., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brues Baltic" authorityYear="1933" box="[454,592,1073,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Pristapenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primaeva">
<emphasis box="[454,472,1073,1097]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[491,592,1073,1097]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">primaeva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was believed to be ancestral to). The name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[128,654,211,1424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
COMMENTS: While the Early Cretaceous genera such as 
<taxonomicName box="[315,465,1192,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Libanobythus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[315,465,1192,1216]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Libanobythus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ENGEL &amp; GRIMALDI" authorityYear="2007" box="[533,654,1192,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Uliobythus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[533,654,1192,1216]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Uliobythus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reminiscent in habitus of the Cenozoic 
<emphasis box="[128,421,1252,1276]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brues" authorityYear="1933" box="[128,279,1252,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Pristapenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pristapenesia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ENGEL &amp; GRIMALDI" authorityYear="2007" box="[308,421,1252,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Zapenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zapenesia</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ENGEL &amp; GRIMALDI" authorityYear="2007" box="[515,654,1252,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Boreobythus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[515,654,1252,1276]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Boreobythus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the typical habitus of a generalized chrysidoid. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ENGEL &amp; GRIMALDI" authorityYear="2007" box="[264,377,1311,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Zapenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,377,1311,1335]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Zapenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently more derived than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ENGEL &amp; GRIMALDI" authorityYear="2007" box="[263,402,1341,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Scolebythidae" genus="Boreobythus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[263,402,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Boreobythus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as evidenced by the reduced pronotal dorsal surface and the reduced wing venation.
</paragraph>
